  **Flux** (also known as **FLUX.1** and **FLUX.2**) is a [text-to-image model](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Text-to-image_model "Text-to-image model") developed by Black Forest Labs (BFL), based in [Freiburg im Breisgau](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freiburg_im_Breisgau "Freiburg im Breisgau"), Germany. Black Forest Labs was founded by former employees of [Stability AI](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stability_AI "Stability AI"). As with other text-to-image models, Flux [generates](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generative_artificial_intelligence "Generative artificial intelligence") [images](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artificial_intelligence_visual_art "Artificial intelligence visual art") from [natural language](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_language "Natural language") descriptions, called _[prompts](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prompt_engineering "Prompt engineering")_.
  
  ## History
  
  \[ [edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Flux_(text-to-image_model)&action=edit&section=1 "Edit section: History")\]
  
  Black Forest Labs (BFL) was founded in 2024 by Robin Rombach, Andreas Blattmann, and Patrick Esser, former employees of Stability AI.[\[2\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-DieZeit-2)[\[3\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-PetaPixel-3) All three founders had previously researched the artificial intelligence image generation at [LMU Munich](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LMU_Munich "LMU Munich") as research assistants under Björn Ommer.[\[4\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-AlleAktien-4)[\[5\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-TrendAT-5)[\[6\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-CapitalDE-6) They published their research results on image generation in 2022, which resulted in creation of [Stable Diffusion](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stable_Diffusion "Stable Diffusion").[\[6\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-CapitalDE-6)[\[7\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Ommer-7) Investors in BFL included venture capital firm [Andreessen Horowitz](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andreessen_Horowitz "Andreessen Horowitz"), [Brendan Iribe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brendan_Iribe "Brendan Iribe"), [Michael Ovitz](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Ovitz "Michael Ovitz"), [Garry Tan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Garry_Tan "Garry Tan"), and [Vladlen Koltun](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vladlen_Koltun "Vladlen Koltun").[\[8\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Announcement-8) The company received an initial investment of [US$](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_dollar "United States dollar") 31million.[\[9\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-TrendingTopics-9)[\[10\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-VentureBeat-funding-10)
  
  In August 2024, Flux was integrated into the [Grok](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grok_(chatbot) "Grok (chatbot)") chatbot developed by [xAI](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/XAI_(company) "XAI (company)") and made available as part of premium feature on [X (formerly Twitter)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Twitter "Twitter").[\[11\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Meedia-11)[\[12\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Handelsblatt-12)[\[13\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-TheVerge-13)[\[14\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Bloomberg-14) Grok later switched to its own text-to-image model [Aurora](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aurora_(text-to-image_model) "Aurora (text-to-image model)") in December 2024.[\[15\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Grok-Aurora-15)
  
  On 18 November 2024, [Mistral AI](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mistral_AI "Mistral AI") announced that its _Le Chat_ chatbot had integrated Flux Pro as its image generation model.[\[16\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Mistral-LeChat-16)[\[17\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-VentureBeat-LeChat-17)
  
  On 21 November 2024, BFL announced the release of Flux.1 Tools, a suite of editing tools designed to be used on top of existing Flux models. The tools consisting of Flux.1 Fill for [inpainting](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inpainting "Inpainting") and outpainting, Flux.1 Depth for control based on extracted [depth map](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth_map "Depth map") of input images and prompts, Flux.1 Canny for control based on extracted [canny edges](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canny_edge_detector "Canny edge detector") of input images and prompts, and Flux.1 Redux for mixing existing input images and prompts. Each tools are available in both _Pro_ and _Dev_ models.[\[18\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Tools-18)[\[19\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-TheDecoder-Tools-19)
  
  In January 2025, BFL announced a partnership with [Nvidia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nvidia "Nvidia") for inclusion of Flux models as foundation models for Nvidia's [Blackwell](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blackwell_(microarchitecture) "Blackwell (microarchitecture)") microarchitecture.[\[20\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-VentureBeat-Nvidia-20) The company also announced the release of Flux Pro Finetuning API, designed for customisation and [fine-tuning](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fine-tuning_(deep_learning) "Fine-tuning (deep learning)") of Flux-generated images and a partnership with German media company [Hubert Burda Media](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hubert_Burda_Media "Hubert Burda Media") for usage of Flux Pro as part of content creation.[\[21\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-VentureBeat-ProFinetuning-21)
  
  On 29 May 2025, BFL announced Flux.1 Kontext, a suite of models that enable in-context image generation and editing, allowing users to prompt with both text and images.[\[22\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Kontext-Announcement-22)[\[23\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-VentureBeat-Kontext-23) Alongside this, BFL Playground, an interface for testing Flux models was released.[\[22\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Kontext-Announcement-22)[\[23\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-VentureBeat-Kontext-23)
  
  On 31 July 2025, BFL announced Flux.1 Krea Dev, a model developed in collaboration with Krea AI that trained to achieve better performance, more varied aesthetics, and better realism compared to existing text-to-image models.[\[24\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Flux-Krea-Announcement-24)
  
  In September 2025, [Adobe Inc.](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adobe_Inc. "Adobe Inc.") announced that [Photoshop (beta)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adobe_Photoshop "Adobe Photoshop") users can use Flux.1 Kontext Pro as a model for its generative fill tool.[\[25\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-CaptureAU-Photoshop-Kontext-25) BFL collaborated with [Meta](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meta_Platforms "Meta Platforms") on Vibes, a video-generation app.[\[26\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-TechCrunch-Vibes-26)
  
  On 25 November 2025, BFL announced the release of Flux.2 model series, consisting of Pro, Flex, Dev, and Apache 2.0-licensed _Klein_ (meaning Little or Small in [German language](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/German_language "German language")) models along with Flux.2 [variational autoencoder](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variational_autoencoder "Variational autoencoder") which also released as open-source software under Apache 2.0 licence. This series claimed improvements for image reference, photorealism, typography, and prompt understanding.[\[27\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-VentureBeat-Flux2-Announcement-27)
  
  ## Models
  
  \[ [edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Flux_(text-to-image_model)&action=edit&section=2 "Edit section: Models")\]
  
  [![](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/VulcanSphere_Anime-style_Self-portrait_%28AnimagineXL_4.0%29.webp/250px-VulcanSphere_Anime-style_Self-portrait_%28AnimagineXL_4.0%29.webp.png)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:VulcanSphere_Anime-style_Self-portrait_(AnimagineXL_4.0).webp)
  
  [![](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/60/VulcanSphere_Alter_Anime-style_Self-portrait_%28AnimagineXL_4.0_%2B_Flux.1_Kontext%29.webp/250px-VulcanSphere_Alter_Anime-style_Self-portrait_%28AnimagineXL_4.0_%2B_Flux.1_Kontext%29.webp.png)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:VulcanSphere_Alter_Anime-style_Self-portrait_(AnimagineXL_4.0_%2B_Flux.1_Kontext).webp)
  
  Demonstration of Flux.1 Kontext Pro ability to modify an existing image
  
  - **Left**: Original image created with AnimagineXL 4.0 (a [text-to-image model](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Text-to-image_model "Text-to-image model") based on [Stable Diffusion](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stable_Diffusion "Stable Diffusion") XL) and post-processed with [Krita](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krita "Krita")
  - **Right**: Modified image created with Flux.1 Kontext Pro. Changes made: Addition of fox ears ( [kemonomimi](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kemonomimi "Kemonomimi")), the position of the left arm, the colors of hair, eyes, headphone, jacket, shirt, pants, and the background
  
  Flux is a series of text-to-image models. The models are based on rectified flow transformer blocks scaled to 12billion parameters.[\[8\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Announcement-8)[\[28\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Hugging_Face-28) Flux.1 models were released under different licences with _Schnell_ (meaning Fast or Quick in German language) released as [open-source software](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Open-source_software "Open-source software") under [Apache License](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apache_License "Apache License"), Dev released as [source-available software](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Source-available_software "Source-available software") under a non-commercial licence (users can obtain a self-serving commercial licence for _Dev_ from BFL), and Pro released as [proprietary software](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proprietary_software "Proprietary software") and only available as [API](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/API "API") that can be licensed by third-party users.[\[29\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Get-Flux-29)[\[30\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-TechCrunch-API-30) Users retained the ownership of resulting output regardless of models used.[\[31\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Dev-licence-31)[\[32\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Pro-API-Agreement-32)
  
  An improved flagship model, Flux 1.1 Pro was released on 2 October 2024.[\[33\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-release-1.1-pro-33)[\[34\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-VentureBeat-1.1-pro-34) Two additional modes were added on 6 November, Ultra which can generate image at four times higher resolution and up to 4 megapixel without affecting generation speed and Raw which can generate hyper-realistic image in the style of [candid photography](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Candid_photography "Candid photography").[\[35\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-PetaPixel-1.1-pro-35)[\[36\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-TheDecoder-raw-36)[\[37\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-1.1-ultra-raw-37)
  
  Flux.1 Kontext is a series with in-context image generation and editing capabilities. It is available in Max, Pro, and Dev models. Max is the highest quality model and can be used to iteratively modify an existing image by using prompt while Pro is optimized to balance quality and speed of generation.[\[22\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Kontext-Announcement-22) Dev is an open-weight model released under non-commercial license, same as Flux.1 Dev.[\[38\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Kontext-dev-38)
  
  Flux.2 models are based on latent flow matching architecture with [Mistral AI's](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mistral_AI "Mistral AI") Mistral-3 model (24billion parameters) for its vision-language model. As with Flux.1, Flux.2 models were also released under different licences with _Klein_ released as open-source software under Apache License, Dev released as source-available software under a non-commercial licence (users can obtain a self-serving commercial licence from BFL), and both Flex and Pro released as proprietary software and only available as API.[\[27\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-VentureBeat-Flux2-Announcement-27)
  
  The models can be used either online or locally by using generative AI user interfaces such as [ComfyUI](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ComfyUI "ComfyUI"), [Recraft Studio](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recraft "Recraft") and [Stable Diffusion WebUI Forge](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stable_Diffusion_WebUI_Forge "Stable Diffusion WebUI Forge") (a [fork](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fork_(software_development) "Fork (software development)") of Automatic1111 WebUI).[\[8\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Announcement-8)[\[39\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-ASCII-Forge-39)
  
  Related to Flux is a [text-to-video model](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Text-to-video_model "Text-to-video model") by Black Forest Labs, under development as of February 2026[\[update\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Flux_(text-to-image_model)&action=edit).[\[8\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Announcement-8)
  
  ## Reception
  
  \[ [edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Flux_(text-to-image_model)&action=edit&section=3 "Edit section: Reception")\]
  
  According to a test performed by _[Ars Technica](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ars_Technica "Ars Technica"),_ the outputs generated by Flux.1 Dev and Flux.1 Pro are comparable with [DALL-E 3](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DALL-E "DALL-E") in terms of prompt fidelity, with the photorealism closely matched [Midjourney](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midjourney "Midjourney") 6 and generated human hands with more consistency over previous models such as Stable Diffusion XL.[\[40\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-ArsTechnica-40)
  
  Flux has been criticised for its very realistic generated images. According to media reports, depictions ranged from an image of [Donald Trump](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donald_Trump "Donald Trump") posing with guns to disturbing scenes, which triggered discussions about ethical implications of Flux models.[\[4\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-AlleAktien-4)[\[13\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-TheVerge-13)
  
  After the release of the model, social media platform [X](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Twitter "Twitter") was flooded with Flux-generated images.[\[41\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-TechCrunch-BFL-41)[\[42\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-RND-42) Black Forest Labs has not provided exact details of the data used to train the model.[\[35\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-PetaPixel-1.1-pro-35) _Ars Technica_ suspected that Flux is based on a large, unauthorised collection of images [scraped from the internet](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_scraping "Web scraping"), a controversial practice with potential legal consequences.[\[40\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-ArsTechnica-40)[\[43\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-Docma-43)
  
  According to a test performed by Japanese technology news website _Gigazine_ for Flux.1 Kontext, the model series has a good understanding of the English language and can easily transfer [style](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Style_(visual_arts) "Style (visual arts)") of the image from photorealistic into anime-style according to prompts given by the user; however, its ability to understand [Japanese](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_language "Japanese language") is quite poor.[\[44\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-GIGAZINE-Kontext-44)
  
  ## Availability
  
  \[ [edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Flux_(text-to-image_model)&action=edit&section=4 "Edit section: Availability")\]
  
  In addition to the official BFL Playground on its website,[\[45\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-45) the Flux models are also widely available through various third-party platforms for creative and professional use. These include repositories on platforms like [Hugging Face](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugging_Face "Hugging Face")[\[46\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-46) and Replicate.[\[47\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flux_(text-to-image_model)#cite_note-47)
  
